{
  "stem": "7157.3",
  "chunk_idx": 8,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 8.5,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 18,
      "text": "You know, there were many organizations after the war to find surviving Jews, and names were published in the paper, you know, like our name was published in various papers in the United States as survivors that were looking for family, you know.",
      "word_count": 43
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 19,
      "text": "It turns out that Judy's aunt, my present wife's aunt, saw this and saw we were looking for some people she knew.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 20,
      "text": "And she showed it to them, that there were some people in Europe looking for them.",
      "word_count": 16
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 21,
      "text": "So we were able to make contact and get some papers.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 22,
      "text": "Because even then, you needed somebody to sponsor you to come to the States.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 18,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 23,
      "text": "So in January 1947, we were actually finally allowed to come to the States.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "No, not my grandmother-- my grandmother never left the ghetto, the Stanislawow ghetto.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 19,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "She was killed in the Stanislawow ghetto.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 20,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "No, my mother had made arrangements for her to leave the ghetto.",
      "word_count": 12
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 20,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "But unfortunately, like, two days later, they killed pretty much every-- two days or three days after we left the Stanislawow ghetto, all the Jews were killed, strung up on telephone wires.",
      "word_count": 32
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 20,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "They were killed, anyway.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 20,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "So my grandmother, in fact-- my mother to this day is having a hard time with that, that she didn't take her mother with us.",
      "word_count": 25
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 20,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "But she listened to the rabbi.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 21,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "They had survived the war, and they were already in New York.",
      "word_count": 12
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 21,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And my Aunt Sarah, which was my father's sister, who was living in New Jersey at this time-- Sarah Gerson-- her husband was-- was still alive, but-- I mean, her husband was alive.",
      "word_count": 33
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 21,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "They both met us.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 21,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "In fact, when we landed in New York, we went to their house first for about a week.",
      "word_count": 18
    }
  ],
